React 19 made ref a regular prop — forwardRef is no longer needed. The migration pattern is:

Before:
```tsx
const Button = forwardRef<HTMLButtonElement, IButtonProps>((props, ref) => (
  <button ref={ref} {...props} />
));
Button.displayName = 'Button';
```

After:
```tsx
const Button = ({ ref, ...props }: IButtonProps & { ref?: React.Ref<HTMLButtonElement> }) => (
  <button ref={ref} {...props} />
);
```

Files to change:
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/retro/Button.tsx (line 40) — uses `forwardRef` imported from react
- platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel/components/retro/Input.tsx (line 9) — uses `forwardRef` imported from react

For Button.tsx: The component destructures props extensively — add ref to the destructuring. The Slot/button Comp pattern means ref goes to the Comp element. Remove the `import { forwardRef } from 'react'` and replace with `import type { Ref } from 'react'`.

For Input.tsx: Same pattern — add ref to the destructuring, pass to the <input> element.

Remove `displayName` assignments since they are only needed with forwardRef (React uses the function name for non-forwarded components, and React Compiler preserves names).

IMPORTANT: The `import * as React from 'react'` pattern is NOT used in these two files — they use named imports. Clean up accordingly.
